Nassau — German Tier III battleship.

The lead ship in the first series of dreadnoughts of the Imperial German Navy. This battleship was notable for reliable armor, good torpedo protection, and a powerful secondary battery. She carried 283 mm guns that were not inferior in many aspects to larger-caliber gun systems adopted by other navies of the world.

Player Opinion

Performance

Nassau is the first ship in the German battleship line. She is similar to Kawachi in turret layout, but has smaller, faster-firing guns. Despite having the smallest caliber guns at Tier III, Nassau can still inflict good damage with this faster rate of fire.

The accuracy on this ship, on the other hand, is noted by players as "hilarious" and very much like Kawachi . Most of the fired shots will tend to miss the target.

Her secondary guns are beyond excellent for its tier, and can provide good protection against enemy destroyers who attempt to get close to the Nassau .

One must be aware also, that this ship has very poor detection range. Most ships you will encounter can shoot at you even before you see them.

Pros:

  • Faster reload time than any other Tier III battleship.
  • Very tough armor that's hard to citadel, and the bow has enough armor to deflect most shells from other battleships.
  • Long-range and high damage secondary guns melt light-armoured ships.
  • Can point six guns fully forward and all her batteries have excellent shooting angles that allow angling and shooting.

Cons:

  • While it has a 1.8 sigma, it still has terrible dispersion and misses a lot.
  • Vulnerable to fires.
  • Low top speed, though still faster than American counterpart South Carolina .
  • Poor AA protection, though it's unlikely she'll encounter enemy carriers.
  • Poor main gun range, though better than Kawachi .
  • Repair Party ( ) consumable has only two (2) charges instead of the usual three (3).
  • The main guns have low penetration, damage, fire chance, and overall damage output.

Optimal Configuration

Upgrades

The recommended upgrades for Nassau are as follows:

  • Slot 1: Main Armaments Modification 1 ( ) helps improve the survival of her main guns.
  • Slot 2: Damage Control System Modification 1 ( ) will improve her overall survival in battle.

Consumables

Nassau can equip the following consumables:

  • Slot 1: Damage Control Party ( )
  • Slot 2: Repair Party ( )

Camouflage

Type 1, 2, or 5 camouflage can be equipped for credits; Types 2 or 5 are recommended at a minimum to reduce the accuracy of incoming shells.

Nassau also has a permanent camouflage called "Jackal", in which she appears during the Halloween scenarios " Saving Translyvania " and " Sunray in the Darkness ".

History

SMS Nassau was the first dreadnought battleship built for the Imperial German Navy, a response to the launching of the British battleship HMS Dreadnought. Nassau was laid down on 22 July 1907 at the Kaiserliche Werft in Wilhelmshaven, and launched less than a year later on 7 March 1908, approximately 25 months after Dreadnought was launched. She was the lead ship of her class of four battleships, which included Posen, Rheinland, and Westfalen.

Nassau saw service in the North Sea in the beginning of World War I, in the II Division of the I Battle Squadron of the German High Seas Fleet. In August 1915, she entered the Baltic Sea and participated in the Battle of the Gulf of Riga, where she engaged the Russian battleship Slava. Following her return to the North Sea, Nassau and her sister ships took part in the Battle of Jutland on 31 May – 1 June 1916. During the battle, Nassau collided with the British destroyer HMS Spitfire. Nassau suffered a total of 11 killed and 16 injured during the engagement.

After World War I, the bulk of the High Seas Fleet was interned in Scapa Flow. As they were the oldest German dreadnoughts, the Nassau-class ships were for the time permitted to remain in German ports. After the German fleet was scuttled, Nassau and her three sisters were surrendered to the victorious powers as replacements for the sunken ships. Nassau was ceded to Japan in April 1920. With no use for the ship, Japan sold her to a British wrecking firm which then scrapped her in Dordrecht, Netherlands.

Historical Inaccuracies

  • Historically traded two 88 mm secondary guns for two 88 mm flak guns. The in-game version, however, trades four 88s for four flak guns.
  • Nassau ’s 1916-17 configuration is missing; all fourteen 88 mm casemated guns were removed.
  • Nassau flies the war ensign of the Kriegsmarine despite serving only in the Imperial German Navy.
  • The Kriegsmarine flag was first adopted in 1935; all four Nassau s were scrapped between 1920 and 1924.
